# Antibody-Antigen Binding Affinity Prediction Model

## Problem Statement

Build a model that predicts the binding affinity between an antibody (heavy chain + light chain) and an antigen, given their amino acid sequences. The model must generalize across antigen families despite severe biases in the training data.

## Dataset Summary

| Property | Value |
|---|---|
| **Primary dataset** | `asd_regression_ready_hla.csv` (164,310 rows, 11 columns) |
| **Full dataset** | `asd_full.csv` (~2.7 GB, mostly fuzzy/boolean labels — not directly usable for regression) |
| **Input features** | `heavy_sequence`, `light_sequence`, `antigen_sequence` |
| **Target** | `processed_measurement` (numeric affinity value) |
| **Unique antigens** | 52 |
| **Unique heavy chains** | 93,879 |
| **Unique light chains** | 3,082 |
| **Source datasets** | 8 (abbd, flab_koenig2017, flab_warszawski2019, abdesign, flab_shanehsazzadeh2023, skempiv2, dlgo, ab-bind) |

### Key Sequence Properties

| Sequence | Length Range | Mean Length |
|---|---|---|
| Heavy chain | 113–227 aa | 121.4 aa |
| Light chain | 104–221 aa | 200.5 aa |
| Antigen | 14–1,283 aa | 449.2 aa |

---

## Critical Bias Analysis

> [!CAUTION]
> **The dataset has extreme antigen-family bias.** A single antigen (Influenza Hemagglutinin, 519aa) dominates **79.5%** of all data (130,629/164,310 rows). The top 3 antigens cover ~93% of the data.

### Bias Breakdown

| Antigen / Family | Rows | % of Data | Source Dataset |
|---|---|---|---|
| Influenza Hemagglutinin (519aa) | 130,629 | 79.5% | abbd |
| Unknown peptide (14aa) | 17,585 | 10.7% | abbd |
| VEGF (395aa) | 4,275 | 2.6% | flab_koenig2017 |
| Influenza HA variant (518aa) | 3,729 | 2.3% | abbd |
| VEGF-related (102aa) | 2,223 | 1.4% | abbd |
| Hen Egg Lysozyme (129aa) | 2,048 | 1.2% | flab_warszawski2019 |
| Lysozyme variant (129aa) | 1,499 | 0.9% | abbd |
| HER2 (1057aa) | 446 | 0.3% | flab_shanehsazzadeh2023 |
| COVID variants (10 × 1283aa) | 360 | 0.2% | dlgo |
| ~32 other antigens | ~1,516 | 0.9% | abdesign, skempiv2, ab-bind |

### Additional Biases

1. **Light chain collapse**: The `abbd` dataset (155K rows) has only **8 unique light chains**, meaning the model could trivially overfit to light chain identity rather than learning general sequence-level interactions.
2. **Mixed affinity scales**: 6 different measurement types with incompatible scales:
   - `-log KD` (152,401 rows): range 5.6–12.4, mean 7.76
   - `kd` (6,769 rows): range 3.7e-5–1461.56
   - `log_enrichment` (3,452 rows): range -4.1–10.2
   - `ddg` (670 rows): range -2.9–8.0
   - `elisa_mut_to_wt_ratio` (658 rows): range 0.01–1.37
   - `ic_50` (360 rows): range 0.001–5.7
3. **Antigen concentration**: 10 antigens account for 99.1% of data; the remaining 42 antigens have <100 samples each.

---

## Proposed Architecture

### High-Level Design

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph Input
        H[Heavy Chain Seq]
        L[Light Chain Seq]
        A[Antigen Seq]
    end

    subgraph "Sequence Encoder (Shared ESM-2 650M)"
        E1[ESM-2 Encoder]
    end

    H --> E1
    L --> E1
    A --> E1

    E1 --> H_EMB[Heavy Embeddings<br/>B × L_h × 1280]
    E1 --> L_EMB[Light Embeddings<br/>B × L_l × 1280]
    E1 --> A_EMB[Antigen Embeddings<br/>B × L_a × 1280]

    H_EMB --> CONCAT[Concatenate H+L<br/>→ Antibody Embeddings]
    L_EMB --> CONCAT

    CONCAT --> CROSS[Cross-Attention<br/>Antibody ↔ Antigen]
    A_EMB --> CROSS

    CROSS --> POOL[Attentive Pooling]

    POOL --> HEAD[Multi-Task Affinity Heads]

    HEAD --> OUT1["-log KD" Head]
    HEAD --> OUT2["KD Head"]
    HEAD --> OUT3["ΔΔG Head"]
    HEAD --> OUT4["Enrichment Head"]
    HEAD --> OUT5["ELISA Head"]
    HEAD --> OUT6["IC50 Head"]
```

### Component Details

#### 1. Protein Language Model Backbone — ESM-2 (650M)

- **Why ESM-2**: Pre-trained on 250M protein sequences; captures evolutionary and structural information from sequence alone. ESM-2 650M balances performance vs. compute.
- **Usage**: Shared encoder for all three input sequences (heavy, light, antigen). Fine-tuned with LoRA (rank 16) to keep memory manageable.
- **Alternative considered**: ESM-3 or AbLang (antibody-specific). AbLang could be used for antibody encoding with ESM-2 for antigen, but the dual-encoder adds complexity; starting with a single shared encoder is simpler and has been shown to work well.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Decision point**: Should we use ESM-2 (general protein) for all sequences, or AbLang/IgBERT for antibody chains + ESM-2 for antigen? The former is simpler; the latter may give better antibody representations. I recommend starting with ESM-2 only, and trying the dual-encoder as an ablation.

#### 2. Cross-Attention Interaction Module

- Antibody tokens (concatenated heavy + light) attend to antigen tokens bidirectionally via 4 layers of cross-attention.
- This models the physical interaction interface rather than just comparing global representations.
- Each layer: `MultiHeadCrossAttention(d=1280, heads=16)` → LayerNorm → FFN → residual.

#### 3. Attentive Pooling

- Learned query vector attends over all cross-attention output tokens to produce a fixed-size interaction vector (dim=512).
- Preferable to mean pooling because binding sites are localized.

#### 4. Multi-Task Affinity Heads

Since the 6 affinity scales are fundamentally different measurements, we use **task-specific prediction heads** sharing the same backbone:

| Head | Scale | Loss | Rows |
|---|---|---|---|
| `-log KD` | 5.6–12.4 | MSE | 152,401 |
| `kd` | log-transformed → MSE | MSE on log(kd) | 6,769 |
| `log_enrichment` | -4.1–10.2 | MSE | 3,452 |
| `ddg` | -2.9–8.0 | MSE | 670 |
| `elisa_ratio` | 0–1.37 | MSE | 658 |
| `ic_50` | log-transformed | MSE on log(ic50) | 360 |

Each head is a 2-layer MLP: `512 → 256 → 1`. Only the relevant head's loss is computed per sample.

---

## Anti-Bias Training Strategy

This is the most critical part of the plan given the dataset characteristics.

### Strategy 1: Antigen-Family-Aware Data Splitting

> [!WARNING]
> **Standard random splitting would leak antigen information.** If the same antigen appears in train and test, the model merely memorizes antigen-specific patterns.

**Approach**: Split by antigen family, not by row.

Group the 52 antigens into ~8 families based on sequence similarity (use CD-HIT or MMseqs2 clustering at 40% sequence identity):
- **Influenza HA family** (2 sequences, ~134K rows)
- **COVID Spike family** (10 sequences, ~360 rows)
- **Lysozyme family** (2 sequences, ~3.5K rows)
- **VEGF family** (1-2 sequences, ~6.5K rows)
- **HER2** (1 sequence, 446 rows)
- **Small antigens** (~35 sequences, ~2K rows)

**Evaluation protocol**:
1. **Primary**: Leave-One-Antigen-Family-Out (LOAFO) cross-validation — train on N-1 families, test on the held-out family. This is the gold-standard for measuring generalization.
2. **Secondary**: Stratified random split within families (80/10/10) — for measuring in-distribution performance.

### Strategy 2: Balanced Sampling During Training

To prevent the model from spending 80% of gradient updates on influenza HA:

```
Sample weight per row = 1 / sqrt(antigen_family_count)
```

This gives:
| Family | Raw count | Effective weight | Effective proportion |
|---|---|---|---|
| Influenza HA | 134,358 | 1/366 ≈ 0.0027 | ~15% |
| COVID Spike | 360 | 1/19 ≈ 0.053 | ~8% |
| Lysozyme | 3,547 | 1/60 ≈ 0.017 | ~25% |
| VEGF | 6,498 | 1/81 ≈ 0.012 | ~32% |
| Others | ~19K | varies | ~20% |

The `sqrt` dampening (vs. full inverse) prevents over-weighting extremely rare families where data is noisy.

### Strategy 3: Antigen Augmentation

To improve generalization to unseen antigens:

1. **Subsequence masking**: Randomly mask 10-15% of antigen tokens during training (forces the model to learn robust features, not memorize specific antigen patterns).
2. **Homolog substitution**: For antigens with known homologs (e.g., different flu strains), randomly swap antigen sequences within the family during training.

### Strategy 4: Regularization Against Antigen Memorization

1. **Gradient reversal on antigen identity**: Add an auxiliary antigen-family classifier with gradient reversal (Domain-Adversarial Neural Networks idea). This penalizes the shared representation for being predictive of antigen identity, encouraging family-invariant features.
2. **Dropout on antigen embeddings**: Higher dropout (0.3) on antigen pathway vs. antibody pathway (0.1) to reduce over-reliance on specific antigen representations.

---

## Training Pipeline

### Phase 1: Pre-processing

```
1. Load asd_regression_ready_hla.csv
2. Drop 11 non-numeric processed_measurement rows (">8.8")  
3. log-transform kd and ic_50 values → unified log scale
4. Cluster antigens into families (MMseqs2, 40% identity)
5. Assign antigen_family_id to each row
6. Create LOAFO splits + stratified random split
```

### Phase 2: Training

| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| **Backbone** | ESM-2 650M (facebook/esm2_t33_650M_UR50D) |
| **Fine-tuning** | LoRA (rank=16, alpha=32) on attention layers |
| **Cross-attention layers** | 4 |
| **Pooling dim** | 512 |
| **Batch size** | 32 (gradient accumulation = 2 → effective 64) |
| **Optimizer** | AdamW, lr=1e-4 (backbone), lr=5e-4 (heads) |
| **Scheduler** | Cosine annealing with 5% warmup |
| **Epochs** | 30 (early stopping patience=5 on val loss) |
| **Max sequence length** | Heavy: 150, Light: 230, Antigen: 600 (covers 95%+ of data) |
| **Mixed precision** | bf16 (H100 native) |
| **GPU** | NVIDIA H100 (80GB) |

### Phase 3: Evaluation

**Regression Metrics** (per affinity type and overall):
- Pearson correlation coefficient (primary metric)
- Spearman rank correlation
- RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error)
- MAE (Mean Absolute Error)
- R² (Coefficient of Determination)
- Concordance Index (CI) — measures pairwise ranking accuracy
- Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) — where applicable

**Ranking & Classification-Derived Metrics**:
- NDCG@k (k=10, 50) — Normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain for ranking antibodies by affinity
- Precision@k for top binders (top 1%, 5%, 10%)
- AUROC and AUPRC for binarized binding (above/below median threshold per affinity type)
- Enrichment Factor at 1% and 5% — how much better than random at identifying top binders

**Calibration & Error Analysis**:
- Predicted vs. Actual scatter plot with density coloring
- Residual distribution histogram per affinity type
- Calibration curve (binned predicted vs. actual means)
- Error vs. sequence similarity to training set (detect extrapolation failures)

**Generalization Metrics**:
- LOAFO results per held-out family (all above metrics)
- Performance on COVID variants (true zero-shot — unseen antigen family)
- Per-antigen-family scatter plots
- Generalization gap (in-distribution vs. LOAFO performance delta)
- Antibody sequence novelty analysis (performance binned by edit distance to nearest training antibody)

**Experiment Tracking**: All metrics logged to **Weights & Biases (wandb)** with per-epoch curves, per-family dashboards, and final summary tables.

